ical and Legal Philosophy, features a number of distinguised contributors addressing the topic of criminal justice. Part I considers "The Moral and Metaphysical Sources of the Criminal Law," with contributions by Michael S. Moore, Lawrence Rosen, and Martin Shapiro. The four chapters in Part II all relate, more or less directly, to the issue of retribution, with papers by Hugo Adam Bedau, Michael Davis, Jeffrie G. Murphy, and R. B. Brandt. In the following part, Dennis F. Thompson, Christopher D. Stone, and Susan Wolf deal with the special problem of criminal responsibility in government-one of great importance in modern society. The fourth and final part, echoing the topic of NOMOS XXIV, Ethics, Economics, and the Law, addresses the economic theory of crime. The section includes contributions by Alvin K. Klevorick, Richard A. Posner, Jules L. Coleman, and Stephen J. Schulhofer. A valuable bibiography on criminal justice by Andrew C. Blanar concludes this volume of NOMOS.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCriminal lawxCongresses. 0aCriminal lawxPhilosophyxCongresses. 0aPunishmentxCongresses. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aBedau, Hugo Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlanar, Andrew C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandt, R.B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapman, John W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aColeman, Jules L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlevorick, Alvin K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Michael S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy,